 <div class="slide active" data-slide="1" data-part="1"><div class="part-banner" style="background:#eaf7f2;color:var(--leaf-dark);"><span>📘 Part 1 of 1</span><span class="part-title">Lesson — Inertia</span></div><h1 class="big-q">Inertia: Why Things Keep Doing What They're Doing</h1><p class="lead">Click <b>Next ➡</b> to begin the adventure!</p><div style="font-size:120px;text-align:center;margin-top:30px;">🚂</div></div>
 <div class="slide" data-slide="2" data-part="1"><div class="part-banner" style="background:#e8f4fb;color:var(--sky-dark);"><span>📘 Session 1 of 2</span><span class="part-title">What Is Inertia?</span></div><div class="two-col"><div><p class="pill">🔭 Today's puzzle</p><h2 class="big-q">Why does a soccer ball EVENTUALLY stop?</h2><p class="lead">You kick a ball. It rolls. It slows. It stops. <b>Why?</b> Did the ball get tired? Did it run out of "go" energy? Or is something else going on?</p><p class="lead">And here's the strange part — astronauts say a ball kicked in space would <b>keep going forever</b>. <i>Forever!</i> What's different up there?</p><div class="callout">🤔 <b>Today's mission:</b> meet the most stubborn rule in the universe — <b>inertia</b>.</div></div><div style="font-size:140px;text-align:center;">⚽→🛑</div></div></div>
 <div class="slide" data-slide="3" data-part="1"><h2 class="big-q">🤔 First: What does "INERTIA" mean?</h2><p class="lead">A 350-year-old discovery by <b>Sir Isaac Newton</b>. He noticed something simple but HUGE about how things move.</p><div class="callout" style="font-size:18px;background:#fff7e6;border-color:#ffd28a;"><b>📜 The big idea:</b><br>➡ Things at <b>REST</b> tend to <b>stay at rest</b>.<br>➡ Things in <b>MOTION</b> tend to <b>stay in motion</b> — going the same direction, at the same speed.<br>➡ Unless something <b>PUSHES or PULLS</b> them.</div><p>That stubborn "keep doing what I'm doing" attitude is what we call <b>inertia</b>.</p></div>
-<div class="slide" data-slide="4" data-part="1"><h2 class="big-q">🪙 MYSTERY #1: The Coin & Card Trick</h2><div class="beat mystery" id="m4"><span class="beat-badge">🕵️ Real-life puzzle</span><p><b>Try this with a parent:</b></p><ul><li>Place an empty cup on the table.</li><li>Lay a flat playing card or stiff piece of paper on TOP of the cup.</li><li>Put a coin on top of the card, right above the cup's opening.</li><li>Flick the card SHARPLY sideways (use a finger flick).</li></ul><p><b>What happens?</b> The card flies off — but the coin <b>FALLS STRAIGHT INTO THE CUP</b>. Magic? Or science?</p><button class="reveal-btn" onclick="document.getElementById('m4').classList.add('mystery-open')">🔍 Show the answer</button><div class="reveal-content"><p><b>Inertia!</b> The coin was <b>at rest</b>. It "wanted" to stay at rest — that's inertia. The card moved too FAST for friction to drag the coin along, so the coin stayed put. Then gravity pulled it straight down into the cup. The coin barely moved sideways at all!</p></div></div></div>
+<div class="slide" data-slide="4" data-part="1"><h2 class="big-q">🪙 MYSTERY #1: The Coin & Card Trick</h2><div class="beat mystery" id="m4"><span class="beat-badge">🕵️ Real-life puzzle</span><p><b>Try this with a parent:</b></p><ul><li>Place an empty cup on the table.</li><li>Lay a flat playing card or stiff piece of paper on TOP of the cup.</li><li>Put a coin on top of the card, right above the cup's opening.</li><li>Flick the card SHARPLY sideways (use a finger flick).</li></ul><p><b>What happens?</b> The card flies off — but the coin <b>FALLS STRAIGHT INTO THE CUP</b>. Magic? Or science?</p><button class="reveal-btn" onclick="document.getElementById('m4').classList.add('mystery-open')">🔍 Show the answer</button><div class="mystery-answer"><p><b>Inertia!</b> The coin was <b>at rest</b>. It "wanted" to stay at rest — that's inertia. The card moved too FAST for friction to drag the coin along, so the coin stayed put. Then gravity pulled it straight down into the cup. The coin barely moved sideways at all!</p></div></div></div>
 <div class="slide" data-slide="5" data-part="1"><h2 class="big-q">🤔 So… do moving things WANT to keep moving?</h2><p class="lead">It can FEEL that way. But it's not really a "want" — it's just how the universe works.</p><div class="reveal-grid"><div class="reveal"><b>🟢 At rest = stays at rest</b><br>A book on the table doesn't suddenly slide off. Something has to push it.</div><div class="reveal"><b>🔵 In motion = stays in motion</b><br>A rolling marble keeps rolling — until friction or a wall stops it.</div><div class="reveal"><b>🔴 Direction matters too</b><br>A ball going north won't suddenly turn south. Inertia keeps direction <i>and</i> speed.</div></div><p class="small">Tap each card!</p></div>
-<div class="slide" data-slide="6" data-part="1"><h2 class="big-q">🪄 MYSTERY #2: The Magic Tablecloth Trick</h2><div class="beat mystery" id="m6"><span class="beat-badge">🕵️ Real-life puzzle</span><p>Magicians whip a tablecloth out from under plates and glasses — and the dishes <b>stay put</b>. How is this possible? Why don't the dishes go flying?</p><button class="reveal-btn" onclick="document.getElementById('m6').classList.add('mystery-open')">🔍 Show the answer</button><div class="reveal-content"><p>Same trick as the coin! The dishes are at REST. Their inertia keeps them in place. If the magician pulls the cloth FAST and STRAIGHT, friction has barely any time to drag the dishes along. The cloth slides out — the dishes stay still. (Don't try this with grandma's good china!) </p></div></div></div>
+<div class="slide" data-slide="6" data-part="1"><h2 class="big-q">🪄 MYSTERY #2: The Magic Tablecloth Trick</h2><div class="beat mystery" id="m6"><span class="beat-badge">🕵️ Real-life puzzle</span><p>Magicians whip a tablecloth out from under plates and glasses — and the dishes <b>stay put</b>. How is this possible? Why don't the dishes go flying?</p><button class="reveal-btn" onclick="document.getElementById('m6').classList.add('mystery-open')">🔍 Show the answer</button><div class="mystery-answer"><p>Same trick as the coin! The dishes are at REST. Their inertia keeps them in place. If the magician pulls the cloth FAST and STRAIGHT, friction has barely any time to drag the dishes along. The cloth slides out — the dishes stay still. (Don't try this with grandma's good china!) </p></div></div></div>
 <div class="slide" data-slide="7" data-part="1"><h2 class="big-q">🛑 But wait… things DO stop on Earth.</h2><p class="lead">A rolling ball stops. A pushed wagon slows down. So why doesn't inertia keep them rolling FOREVER?</p><p>Because there's usually something pushing back: <b>FRICTION</b>.</p><div class="reveal-grid"><div class="reveal"><b>🌿 Grass grabs a soccer ball</b><br>Tiny bumps and blades create friction.</div><div class="reveal"><b>🛣 Asphalt grabs a tire</b><br>Even smooth road has texture.</div><div class="reveal"><b>💨 Air pushes back</b><br>Even the air slows things down — it's a force called <i>air resistance</i>.</div></div><div class="callout">💡 <b>Key insight:</b> A moving thing only stops because <b>something is pushing back</b>. Without friction or air, it would keep going FOREVER.</div></div>
 <div class="slide" data-slide="8" data-part="1"><h2 class="big-q">🧪 Demo: Friction Showdown</h2><p class="lead"><b>Materials:</b> 1 small toy car (or marble) · 3 different surfaces (carpet, wood floor, smooth tile or glass)</p><ol style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.8;"><li>Roll the car the SAME WAY on each surface.</li><li>Time how long it takes to stop, OR measure how far it goes.</li><li>Order the surfaces from MOST friction → LEAST friction.</li></ol><div class="callout"><b>💭 Predict first:</b> Which surface will stop the car fastest? Why?<br><b>Then check:</b> were you right? Carpet usually wins (most friction). Tile lets things glide.</div><p class="small">📓 Record your results — they're part of homework #2.</p></div>
 <div class="slide" data-slide="9" data-part="1"><h2 class="big-q">🎉 End of Session 1</h2><p class="lead">You've met inertia and discovered why moving things stop on Earth.</p><div class="callout">📦 <b>What you've banked so far:</b><br>✓ Things at rest stay at rest. Moving things stay moving.<br>✓ This stubborn rule is called <b>inertia</b>.<br>✓ On Earth, <b>friction</b> is usually what stops moving things.</div><p>Take a break! In Session 2, we'll see how <b>weight</b> changes inertia — and why a truck is way harder to stop than a bicycle.</p></div>
 <div class="slide" data-slide="10" data-part="2"><div class="part-banner" style="background:#fdeeea;color:var(--animal);"><span>📘 Session 2 of 2</span><span class="part-title">Mass, Force & The Real World</span></div><h2 class="big-q">🚛 Why is a TRUCK harder to stop than a BICYCLE?</h2><p class="lead">Both have inertia. But they don't feel the same. Why?</p><p>Two words: <b>more mass</b>.</p><div class="callout">📐 <b>The rule:</b> The <b>more mass</b> something has, the <b>more inertia</b> it has — meaning the <b>more force</b> you need to start it, stop it, or change its direction.</div></div>
 <div class="slide" data-slide="11" data-part="2"><h2 class="big-q">⚖️ Demo: Heavy vs Light</h2><p class="lead"><b>Materials:</b> One empty backpack and one full of books · A smooth floor</p><ol style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.8;"><li>Push the empty backpack across the floor with one finger. Easy?</li><li>Now push the full one. Same finger, same effort.</li><li>Notice: did it move at all? How hard would you need to push?</li></ol><p>The full backpack has <b>more mass</b>. More mass = more inertia. So you need <b>more push</b> to get it going.</p><div class="callout">🧠 Same is true for stopping! A loaded truck takes MUCH longer to brake than an empty one.</div></div>
-<div class="slide" data-slide="12" data-part="2"><h2 class="big-q">🚗 MYSTERY #3: The Seatbelt Mystery</h2><div class="beat mystery" id="m12"><span class="beat-badge">🕵️ Real-life puzzle</span><p>You're in a car. The driver SLAMS on the brakes. Without a seatbelt, you'd <b>fly forward</b> — even though the car is the thing that stopped, not you. Why?</p><button class="reveal-btn" onclick="document.getElementById('m12').classList.add('mystery-open')">🔍 Show the answer</button><div class="reveal-content"><p>Your <b>body had inertia</b>! When the car was moving, your body was moving too. When the car suddenly stopped, your body still wanted to keep going forward at the original speed. The seatbelt is the force that stops <i>you</i> — without it, the windshield would do that job (and that's really, really bad).</p><p><b>Lesson:</b> Seatbelts save lives because they apply the force that your inertia needs.</p></div></div></div>
-<div class="slide" data-slide="13" data-part="2"><h2 class="big-q">🚀 MYSTERY #4: Why Astronauts PUSH OFF the Walls</h2><div class="beat mystery" id="m13"><span class="beat-badge">🕵️ Real-life puzzle</span><p>In space, astronauts push gently off a wall — and FLOAT all the way across the room. They don't slow down. They just keep going until they hit the other wall. Why doesn't that work on Earth?</p><button class="reveal-btn" onclick="document.getElementById('m13').classList.add('mystery-open')">🔍 Show the answer</button><div class="reveal-content"><p>In space there's <b>no friction and (almost) no air</b>. Once an astronaut is moving, inertia keeps them moving — at the same speed, in the same direction — until they bump into something. On Earth, gravity pulls you down and friction with the floor stops you fast. Space shows pure inertia in action!</p></div></div></div>
-<div class="slide" data-slide="14" data-part="2"><h2 class="big-q">🪙 MYSTERY #5: The Coin Tower Trick</h2><div class="beat mystery" id="m14"><span class="beat-badge">🕵️ Real-life puzzle</span><p><b>Try this:</b> stack 5 coins on top of each other. Use a butter knife or ruler to FLICK the BOTTOM coin sideways — sharp and fast. The bottom coin shoots out, and the rest of the stack <b>stays standing</b>. How?!</p><button class="reveal-btn" onclick="document.getElementById('m14').classList.add('mystery-open')">🔍 Show the answer</button><div class="reveal-content"><p>The top 4 coins were <b>at rest</b>. Their inertia wanted them to stay at rest. The flick was so quick that there wasn't enough TIME for friction to drag them sideways. The bottom coin slipped out, and the others dropped straight down — landing on the table where the bottom one used to be.</p></div></div></div>
