+<div class="slide" data-slide="16" data-part="2"><h2 class="big-q">🌳 MYSTERY #6: Why does a falling leaf flutter?</h2><div class="beat mystery" id="m16"><span class="beat-badge">🕵️ Real-life puzzle</span><p>Drop a rock — it falls FAST and STRAIGHT. Drop a leaf — it floats, flutters, drifts sideways. They're both falling. Why so different?</p><button class="reveal-btn" onclick="document.getElementById('m16').classList.add('mystery-open')">🔍 Show the answer</button><div class="mystery-answer"><p>A leaf has very <b>little mass</b> — so very little inertia. The tiny push of <b>air resistance</b> can easily nudge it sideways. The rock has way more mass and inertia, so air can't move it much — it falls almost straight. Mass + inertia + air = the difference!</p></div></div></div>
 <div class="slide" data-slide="17" data-part="2"><h2 class="big-q">🌍 Inertia is everywhere</h2><p class="lead">Once you see it, you'll spot inertia <i>all day long</i>.</p><div class="reveal-grid"><div class="reveal"><b>🚌 Bus brakes suddenly</b><br>Standing passengers lurch forward. Inertia.</div><div class="reveal"><b>🥤 Drink in a moving car</b><br>Slosh forward when the car stops. Inertia.</div><div class="reveal"><b>🧸 Toy on a wagon</b><br>You jerk the wagon — toy slides backward. Inertia kept the toy still.</div><div class="reveal"><b>🪂 A skydiver opens a parachute</b><br>Suddenly slows because the parachute creates a HUGE force against inertia.</div><div class="reveal"><b>🥏 Spinning frisbee</b><br>Wants to keep spinning AND moving in a straight line.</div><div class="reveal"><b>🚂 Long train</b><br>Takes over a kilometer to stop. Massive mass = massive inertia.</div></div></div>
 <div class="slide" data-slide="18" data-part="2"><h2 class="big-q">✨ What you now know</h2><ul class="checklist"><li><b>Inertia</b> = things keep doing what they're doing (rest stays rest, motion stays motion)</li><li>This is <b>Newton's 1st Law of Motion</b></li><li>On Earth, <b>friction</b> and <b>air resistance</b> usually stop moving things</li><li>In space, things keep going forever (no friction!)</li><li>More <b>mass</b> = more <b>inertia</b> (trucks need bigger brakes than bikes)</li><li>Seatbelts work BECAUSE of inertia — your body wants to keep moving when the car stops</li></ul><div class="callout">🎉 You've unlocked one of the universe's most fundamental rules. Try the homework and quiz next!</div></div>
